The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 New Delhi, July 13 (PTI): The railways have reduced the advance reservation period for booking of tickets from 90 days to 60 days, a release said today.

 Bookings done before July 15 under the current advance reservation period of 90 days will be valid, it said. There will be no change in the limit of 360 days for advance booking for foreign tourists and 30 days for some day-time express trains like Taj Express. 

 Kinshasa (AFP): Indian UN peacekeepers have been accused of gold trafficking with Rwandan Hutu rebels in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo, according to UN documents and witnesses. They exchanged food and information for gold and dollars for some months in 2005 and 2006, UN officials said. However, Indian Army spokesman Col Sakhuja said in Delhi: There are no such reports with us.

 New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has refused to stay the order allowing the extradition of Maninder Pal Singh Kohli, accused of raping and killing British teenager Hannah Foster. Kohlis petition challenging the order will be heard on July 20.

 New Delhi: Bengal and 15 other states with significant Muslim population are lagging in efforts to modernise madarsas and recruit Urdu teachers, the Centre has said. These states have been given 15 days to submit fresh proposals on how they plan to improve their performance.

 Bangalore (PTI): A self-styled human rights and social activist has been arrested on the charge of sexually abusing minor girls in free hostels run by him. P.P. Ramesh, who had earlier served a life sentence for a murder, had convinced poor couples to admit their daughters to the hostels, police said. 

 Kathmandu (PTI): Actress Manisha Koiralas grandmother and Nepal Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koiralas sister-in-law Shushila Koirala passed away on Friday. Shushila, 84, was the wife of B.P. Koirala, the first elected Prime Minister of Nepal.




